Data Science Project Report – Loan Default Risk & Rating

Problem statement
- Classify loans as “good” vs “bad” (default risk) and bucket them into rating-style risk bands (AAA → CCC) so high-risk loans are flagged early.

Dataset
- Source: `Loan_Default.csv` (provided).
- Target label: `Status` (1 = bad/default risk, 0 = good).
- ID column: `ID` (dropped from features).
- Mixed numeric + categorical columns (see code for auto-detection).

Approach (aligned to the provided end-sem guidelines)
1) Model choice (Guideline #1) – Logistic Regression (balanced class weights) for speed + interpretability. Metrics: accuracy, F1, ROC-AUC on held-out test set. Running time: recorded train/test wall-clock times.
2) Preprocessing:
   - Categorical: SimpleImputer(most_frequent) → OneHotEncoder(ignore unknowns).
   - Numeric: SimpleImputer(median) → StandardScaler.
3) Randomized scaling technique (Guideline #2) – GaussianRandomProjection applied to numeric features to reduce dimensionality; trained on a 40% stratified subsample to simulate “smaller dataset” vs. full dataset. Reason: projection lowers feature dimension, reducing linear-model fit cost and speeding training with minimal accuracy loss.
4) Outputs:
   - Metrics per run (train/test time, accuracy, F1, ROC-AUC).
   - Rating buckets from predicted default probabilities (quantile-based AAA … CCC) saved as CSV.
5) Running time improvement (Guideline #3):
   - See “Results & Comparison” for time deltas and asymptotic discussion.
6) Conclusion & future work (Guideline #4):
   - See “Conclusion & Future Work” section below.

