Results & comparison (actual numbers from `artifacts/summary.json`)
- Baseline (full data):
  - Train time: 3.45 s; Test time: 0.24 s.
  - Accuracy: 0.839; F1: 0.685; ROC-AUC: 0.867.
- Random projection on 40% data:
  - Train time: 1.52 s (≈2.3× faster); Test time: 0.19 s.
  - Accuracy: 0.835; F1: 0.673; ROC-AUC: 0.862.
- Observation: Training sped up materially with only ~0.004 drop in accuracy, ~0.012 drop in F1, ~0.005 drop in ROC-AUC.
- Asymptotic note: For a linear model on d features and n samples, fit cost is ~O(ndk) with randomized projection (k ≪ d) vs. ~O(nd) plus denser one-hot expansion if left unprojected; projection reduces effective feature dimensionality, improving constant factors and memory footprint.

Asymptotic running time (explicit, with our numbers)
- Let n = 47,574 samples (post train/test split ~38k train, ~9.5k test). Let d_cat be one-hot categorical dimension (data-dependent) and d_num = 11 numeric features.
- Baseline pipeline:
  - OneHotEncoder: produces d_cat dummy columns; total dimensionality d = d_cat + d_num.
  - LogisticRegression (saga/ lbfgs) per-iteration cost ≈ O(n * d); with T iterations, O(T * n * d). In practice, max_iter=500 caps T.
- Random projection pipeline:
  - Numeric block is projected to k components (here k = min(10, d_num) = 10). Dimensionality becomes d' = d_cat + k (k < d_num).
  - Per-iteration cost ≈ O(T * n * d') with d' < d, so we reduce the feature factor and observed wall-clock drops from 3.45 s → 1.52 s.
- Empirical vs. asymptotic alignment:
  - Feature reduction (d' < d) + 40% subsampling (n' ≈ 0.4n) together cut the dominant nd term; wall-clock improved by ~2.3×, consistent with scaling n and d down.

Rating buckets
- Ratings derived from predicted default probabilities (quantiles: 10/25/50/70/85/95%). Output files:
  - `artifacts/ratings_baseline_full.csv`
  - `artifacts/ratings_random_proj_40pct.csv`
- Use these to count distribution per bucket (AAA safest to CCC riskiest) and to flag the top-risk tail (e.g., CCC/B buckets) for early intervention.

Conclusion & future work (Guideline #4)
- Conclusion: Randomized projection with a reduced training subset achieved ~2.3× faster training while keeping ROC-AUC within ~0.005 of full-data performance, satisfying the scaling requirement with minimal accuracy trade-off.
- Future work:
  - Try HistGradientBoosting (handles NaNs natively) or Gradient Boosting Trees for non-linear patterns.
  - Calibrate probabilities (Platt/Isotonic) for better rating thresholds.
  - Cost-sensitive thresholds to prioritize recall on bad loans.
  - Model explainability (per-feature coefficients or SHAP) for governance.
  - Hyperparameter search on projection size and regularization strength.

